ay 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Tamon Maru No.12|1889|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship struck a mine and sank off [[Shanghai]], China.<ref name=HW222>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyard.info/ships/ships.asp?entryid=222 |title=Nizam |publisher=The Yard |accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-774||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] north west of Ireland ({{coord|49|58|N|11|51|W}}) by {{HMS|Bentinck|K314|6}} and {{HMS|Calder|K349|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 44 crew.<ref name=U774>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u774.htm |title=U-774 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-1001||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC/41]] [[submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean south west of [[Land's End]], [[Cornwall]], United Kingdom ({{coord|49|19|N|10|23|W}}) by {{HMS|Byron|K508|6}} and {{HMS|Fitzroy|K553|6}} (both {{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 46 crew.<ref name=U1001>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u1001.htm |title=U-1001 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine chaser|UJ 301||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The submarine chaser was bombed and set afire in a Soviet air raid on Hela. She was towed out of the port and scuttled by {{ship|German minesweeper|R 71||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref name=UJ301>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?142872 |title=UJ-301 (+1945) |publisher=Wrecksite |date=11 October 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Vale||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk by Soviet aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wio.ru/fleet/sunk/baltic.htm |title=German ships sunk by Soviet aircraft |publisher=Redfleet |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MS|Weserstein||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk by Soviet aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wio.ru/fleet/sunk/baltic.htm |title=German ships sunk by Soviet aircraft |publisher=Redfleet |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German submarine tender|Wilhelm Bauer||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[submarine tender]] was bombed and sunk by Allied aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.german-navy.de/kriegsmarine/ships/fleettender/wilhelmbauer/history.html |title=Wilhelm Bauer&nbsp;\u2013 History |author= |date=25 June 2003 |work=German Naval History |publisher= |accessdate=19 July 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|YMS-103}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[minesweeper]] was heavily damaged by a mine off Okinawa ({{coord|26|13|N|127|54|E}}). Five of her 32 crew were killed. She was beached and abandoned as a total loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/9523.html |title=YMS-103 of the US Navy |publisher=www.uboat.net |accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fold3.com/image/1/295831144 |title=Loss report of YMS-103 |publisher=www.fold3.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==9 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=9 April 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German cruiser|Admiral Scheer||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Deutschland|cruiser}} was sunk in a [[Royal Air Force]] air raid on [[Kiel]], [[Schleswig-Holstein]].\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Albert Jensen||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in the [[Baltic Sea]]