ag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy CU 65]]: The [[T2 tanker]] collided with {{SS|Nashbulk||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}) in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|37|44|N|64|40|W}}), caught fire and was abandoned.<ref name=CU65W>{{cite web|url=http://www.warsailors.com/convoys/cu65.html |title=Convoy CU 65 |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=Mihiel>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmm.org/natlantic.html |title=U.S. Ships Sunk, Damaged or Detained in North Atlantic During World War II |publisher=USMM.org |accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=T2QRS>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/T2Q.html |title=T2 TANKERS - Q - R - S |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-677||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was destroyed at [[Hamburg]] in a British air raid.<ref name=U677>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u677.htm |title=U-677 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-747||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was badly damaged by bombs at [[Hamburg]] in an American air raid. She was scuttled on 3 May 1945.<ref name=U747>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u747.htm |title=U-747 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-804||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40]] [[submarine]] was sunk in the [[Kattegat]] off [[Gothenburg]], Sweden ({{coord|57|58|N|11|15|E}}) by [[de Havilland Mosquito]] aircraft of [[No. 143 Squadron RAF|143 Squadron]] and [[No. 235 Squadron RAF|235 Squadron]], [[Royal Air Force]] with the loss of all 55 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-843||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40]] submarine was sunk in the Kattegat west of Gothenburg ({{coord|57|32|N|11|23|E}}) by a rocket attack by de Havilland Mosquito aircraft of 235 Squadron, Royal Air Force with the loss of 44 of her 56 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-982||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was bombed and destroyed at [[Hamburg]] in a [[Royal Air Force]] air raid.<ref name=U982>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u982.htm |title=U-982 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-1065||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC/41]] [[submarine]] was sunk in the Skaggerak ({{coord|57|58|N|11|15|E}} by a rocket attack by de Havilland Mosquito aircraft of 143 and 235 Squadrons, Royal Air Force with the loss of all 45 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-2509||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type XXI submarine|Type XXI]] [[submarine]] was bombed and sunk at Hamburg in a Royal Air Force air raid.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref name=U2509>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u2509.htm |title=U-2509 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-2514||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type XXI submarine|Type XXI]] [[submarine]] was bombed and sunk at Hamburg in a Royal Air Force air raid.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref name=U2514>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u2514.htm |title=U-2514 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-2516||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type XXI submarine|Type XXI]] [[submarine]] was sunk at Kiel in a British air raid. The wreck was scrapped post-war.<ref name=U2516>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u2516.htm |title=U-2516 |publisher=Uboa