ost|DE-144|6}} and {{USS|Stanton|DE-247|6}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of all 57 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German patrol boat|Vs-58||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''[[Vorpostenboot]]'' struck a mine and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] north-east of [[Kiel]], [[Schleswig-Holstein]] ({{coord|54|32|N|10|38|E}}).<ref>{{csr |register=MSI |id=5614999 |shipname=Vs.58 |accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==16 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=16 April 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Athelduke||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: [[Convoy FS 1784]]: The [[tank ship|tanker]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] east of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] ({{coord|55|39|N|1|31|W}}) by {{GS|U-1274||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). One crew was killed.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ship/3491.html |title=Athelduke |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Bryant|DD-665|6}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Fletcher|destroyer}} was severely damaged off [[Okinawa]], Japan by a ''[[kamikaze]]'' attack with the loss of 34 of her crew. She was out of action for the rest of the war.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese escort|CD-73||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Type C escort ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off Japan ({{coord|39|36|N|142|05|E}}) by {{USS|Sunfish|SS-281|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=Sunfish/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Cap Guir||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk by a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Douglas A-20 Havoc]] aircraft off [[\u00d6land]], Sweden with the loss of 756 lives.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref>{{csr |register=MSI |id=1148927 |shipname=Cap 