ater, her anti-aircraft guns remaining in action until they ran out of ammunition on 4 May. She later was raised by the [[Soviet Union]] and sunk in weapons testing in July 1947.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Gold Shell||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was sunk in the North Sea by a Kriegsmarine [[Seehund]] midget submarine.<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Manryu Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean off Japan ({{coord|39|36|N|142|05|E}}) by {{USS|Sunfish|SS-281|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). 41 crewmen were killed.<ref name=Sunfish>{{cite DANFS | title = Sunfish | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/submar/ss281.htm | accessdate = 4 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Manryu_t.htm |title=Manryu Maru |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Monarch|1916|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cable ship was torpedoed and sunk in the North Sea off [[Orfordness]], [[Suffolk]] by a Kriegsmarine Seehund midget submarine.<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German landing craft|PiLB 554||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The PiLB 41 type landing craft was sunk in the Baltic Sea, either by [[Naval mine|mines]] or by Soviet [[motor torpedo boat]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_amph_pilb41.htm |title=PiBL 41 type landing craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=53730 |title=Soviet Naval Battles-Baltic |publisher=Soviet-Empire |accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Pringle|DD-477|6}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Fletcher|destroyer|2}} was sunk in the Pacific Ocean off Okinawa, Japan by a kamikaze aircraft attack with the loss of 78 of her 336 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-15||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-2 minesweeper]] was sunk in the [[Adriatic Sea]] by Royal Navy motor torpedo boats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=759 |title=German coastal minesweeper Type R-2 |publisher=Warshipsww2.Eu |accessdate=2 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007025553/http://www.warshipsww2.eu/lode.php?language=E&period=&idtrida=759 |archive-date=7 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Toko Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean south of [[Honshu]] by {{USS|Sea Dog|SS-401|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-78|1940|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was shelled and sunk at [[Pillau]], [[East Prussia]] by Soviet shore-based artillery.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-880||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXC/40]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|47|18|N|30|26|W}}) by {{USS|Frost|DE-144|6}} and {{USS|Stanton|DE-247|6}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of all 49 crew.<ref name=Croatan>{{cite DANFS | title = Croatan | url = http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/carriers/cve25.txt | accessdate = 11 January 2012 }}</ref><ref name=U880>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u880.htm |title=U-880 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-1274||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC/41]] [[submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the North Sea north of [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], United Kingdom ({{coord|55|36|N|1|24|W}}) by {{HMS|Viceroy|L21|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 44 crew.<ref name=U1274>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u1274.htm |title=U-1274 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==17 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=17 April 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German seaplane tender|Boelke||2}} \n|flag={{luftwaffe|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Karl Meyer|seaplane tender}} was bombed and sunk off the [[Hel Peninsula]] by Soviet bombers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_cv_karl_meyer.htm |title=Karl Meyer Seaplane Tenders, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|MTB 697}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Fairmile D motor torpedo boat]] was sunk by a [[naval mine|mine]] in the [[Adriatic Sea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/17234.html |title=HMS MTB 697 of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese minesweeper|Noshiro Maru No. 2 Go||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The auxiliary minesweeper was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_esc_aux_ms.htm |title=Auxiliary Minesweepers of WW II, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=22 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Sonjo Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was sunk by a mine in the [[Yangtze]] near where it empties into the [[East China Sea]] on \"Middle Ground\" off [[Shanghai]], China ({{coord|31|13|N|121|52|E}}). Five troops and eighteen crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/W-29_t.htm |title=Japanese Minesweepers |publisher=C