ships/germany/ger_conc_lss2.htm|title=Auxiliary landing Fire Support ships of WWII, Converted Merchant Craft, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://wio.ru/fleet/sunk/baltic.htm |title=ships sunk in the Baltic by soviet aircraft |publisher=Rufleet |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soviet-empire.com/ussr/viewtopic.php?f=149&t=55255&sid=b64d81afc6dc3bf6ebf262ded5ddeaf9 |title=Soviet torpedo bomber victories during WWII |publisher=Sovietempire.com |accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.historisches-marinearchiv.de/projekte/landungsfahrzeuge/artillerietraeger/ausgabe.php?where_value=781 |title=SAT 5 Robert M\u00fcller 6 |publisher=www.historisches-marinearchiv.de |accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Swiftscout||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|145|nmi|km}} north east of [[Cape Henry]], [[North Carolina]] ({{coord|37|30|N|73|03|W}}) by {{GS|U-857||2}} or {{GS|U-879||2}} (both {{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 47 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Chancellorsville||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}).<ref name=Swiftscout>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3496.html |title=Swiftscout |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Teizui Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo liner]] was damaged by a mine at the west entrance of the [[Shimoneseki Strait]] off [[Yawata]], Japan ({{coord|34|05|N|130|50|E}}) and beached and abandoned.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Teizui_t.htm |title=Ex-German Merchants in Japanese Service |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==19 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=19 April 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|s