321||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of eight of her 24 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{MV|Clova|1937|2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}) and the St Abb's lifeboat ([[File:Flag of the Royal National Lifeboat Institution.svg|22px|border]]) [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]].<ref name=Gasray>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/3483.html |title=Gasray |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German patrol boat|Helmi S\u00f6hle||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: the [[patrol boat]] was sunk in the [[Kattegat]] by [[de Havilland Mosquito]] aircraft of [[No. 143 Squadron RAF|143]], [[No. 235 Squadron RAF|235]], [[No. 248 Squadron RAF|248]] and [[No. 333 Squadron RAF|333 Squadrons]], [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese oiler|Kamoi||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[tank ship|oiler]] was bombed and damaged by United States [[Far East Air Force (United States)|Far East Air Force]] [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] aircraft at Hong Kong. She sank on 8 April in very shallow waters. The crew abandoned her on 13 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Kamoi_t.htm|title=Japanese Auxiliary Seaplane Tenders |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=7 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese guard boat|Kiho Maru No. 1 Go||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=The auxiliary guard boat was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/japan/jap_esc_aux_pc.htm |title=Auxiliary Patrol and guard boats, Japan |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kine Maru||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk by [[Martin PBM Mariner]] aircraft of the [[United States Navy]] ({{coord|22|24|N|115|28|E}}). Fifty-six passengers,