royer|Amatsukaze|1939|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Kager\u014d|destroyer}} was bombed and damaged in the [[Strait of Formosa]] {{convert|6|nmi|km}} east of [[Amoy]], China ({{coord|24|30|N|118|10|E}}) by [[North American B-25 Mitchell]] aircraft of the [[United States Army Air Force]]. She was beached at the entrance to Amoy harbor, but salvage was abandoned two days later after further damage by a storm, and she was scuttled on 10 April. Forty-four crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Amatsu_t.htm |title=Long Lancers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=6 April 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Araosan Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy SASI-45: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the Strait of Formosa by {{USS|Hardhead|SS-365|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) with the loss of 57 lives.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref name=Mitsui>{{cite web |url=http://www.theshipslist.com/ships/lines/mitsui.shtml |title=Mitsui company |publisher=www.theshipslist.com |accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Bush|DD-529|6}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Fletcher|destroyer|2}} was sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off [[Okinawa]], Japan ({{Coord|27|16|N|127|48|E}}) by a Japanese [[kamikaze]] attack with the loss of 87 of her 314 crew.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese escort|CD-1||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy HOMO-03: The [[Type C escort ship]] was sunk in [[Fotou Bay, China]] south west of [[Amoy]] ({{coord|23|55|N|117|40|E}}) by North American B-25 Mitchell aircraft of the 345th Bomb Group, United States Army Air Force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/CD-1_t.htm |title=Japanese Escorts |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese escort|CD-134||2}} \n|