DM-32) at Kerama Retto, 14 April 1945 (80-G-330108).jpg|thumb|USS ''Lindsey'']]World War II: The {{sclass-|Allen M. Sumner|destroyer}} was severely damaged off Okinawa by a kamikaze attack with the loss of 57 of her crew. Repairs took until 6 March 1946 to complete.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|LST-493}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=The [[landing ship tank]] ran aground and sank off [[Plymouth, Devon]], United Kingdom ({{coord|50|20|N|04|09|W}}).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/11553.html |title=LST-493 of the US Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Mannert L. Abele|DD-733|6}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: A Japanese [[kamikaze]] attack using an [[Aichi D3A]] or [[Yokosuka MXY7 Ohka]] aircraft sank the {{sclass-|Allen M. Sumner|destroyer|2}} in the [[Pacific Ocean]] {{convert|70|nmi|km}} north west of Okinawa ({{coord|27|15|00|N|136|30|00|E}}). {{USS|LSM(R)-189}} and {{USS|LSM(R)-190}} (both {{navy|USA|1912}}), rescued the survivors.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Nordsj\u00f8||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: De Havilland Mosquito aircraft of 143, 235, 248 and 333 Squadrons, Royal Air Force bombed and sank the coaster at Porsgrunn, Norway. Raised post-war, repaired and returned to service.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref name=HomeN>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsn.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet&nbsp;\u2013 WW II, Ships starting with N |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref><!--Incorrect date given in ref, see refs for Dione and Traust for confirmation of date-->\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese submarine|Ro-64||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: A [[naval mine|mine]] sank the [[Japanese Type L submarine]] in [[Hiroshima Bay]], Japan while she was on a training mission. Eighty people were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com