viet]] [[Douglas A-20 Havoc]] aircraft off the [[Hel Peninsula]], Poland. 970 killed.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5602465|shipname=Karlsruhe |accessdate=27 October 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kosho Maru No. 2 Go||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary [[guard ship|guardboat]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Pacific Ocean]] by {{USS|Parche|SS-384|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Misago Maru No. 1||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary [[minesweeper]] was torpedoed and sunk in the Pacific Ocean off the Japanese coast by {{USS|Parche|SS-384|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|T16||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Type 37 torpedo boat]] was bombed and sunk by Allied aircraft at [[Fredrikshavn]], Denmark.<ref>{{csr |register=MSI |id=6112437 |shipname=T16 |accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German torpedo boat|TA45||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Ariete|torpedo boat|2}} was sunk in the [[Adriatic Sea]] by {{ship|HMMTB|670}} and {{ship|HMMTB|697}} (both {{navy|UK}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.steelnavy.com/RMAriete.htm |title=RMAriete.htm |publisher=SteelNavy.com |accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==14 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=14 April 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Belgian Airman||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Belgium}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk off [[Chesapeake Bay]], [[Maryland]], United States ({{coord|36|09|N|75|05|W}}) by {{GS|U-857||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 47 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Harold A. Jordan||2}} ({{flag|United States|1912}}).\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese escort|CD-31||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Type C escort ship]] was torpedoed and sunk in Hiyo Inlet, Saishu Island ({{coord|33|25|N|126|15|E}}), by {{USS|Tirante|SS-420|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Sank in shallow water and only partially submerged. Thirty-nine crewmen were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/CD-31_t.htm |title=Japanese Escorts |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Goenoeng Telang'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The fishing vessel was shelled and sunk in the [[Indian Ocean]] by {{HNLMS|O 24}} ({{navy|Netherlands}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref name=O24>{{cite web |url=http://www.dutchsubmarines.com/boats/boat_o24.htm |title=Boar O-24 |publisher=Dutch Submarines |accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Juzan Maru||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: Convoy MOSI-02: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in Hiyo Inlet, Saishu Island ({{coord|33|25|N|126|15|E}}), by {{USS|Tirante|SS-420|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Thirty-three crewmen were killed.<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Juzan_t.htm |title=Juzan Maru |publisher=www.combinedfleet.com |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kako Go||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[coastal trading vessel|coaster]] was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Java Sea]] by {{USS|Gabilan|SS-252|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/><ref>{{cite web|title=Kako Go|url=http://wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?175455|publisher=Wrecksite|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese escort|Nomi||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Mikura|escort ship|1}} was torpedoed and sunk in Hiyo Inlet, Saishu Island ({{coord|33|25|N|126|15|E}}), by {{USS|Tirante|SS-420|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Sank in shallow water and only partially submerged. One hundred and thirty-four crewmen were killed including her captain.<ref name=\"Japanese Minesweepers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/Nomi_t.htm |title=Japanese Minesweepers |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German minesweeper|R-126||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[R boat|Type R-41 minesweeper]] was sunk in The [[Great Belt]] by [[naval mine|mines]].<ref name=\"Warshipsww2.Eu\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Shonan Maru No. 1||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|desc=World War II: The coaster was torpedoed and sunk in the Java Sea by {{USS|Gabilan|SS-252|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}).<ref name=seekrieg194504/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Sigsbee||2}} \n|flag={{navy|USA|1912}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Fletcher|destroyer}} was severely damaged off [[Okinawa]], Japan by a [[kamikaze]] attack. Repairs took until 28 September to complete.\n}} \n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Soviet torpedo boat|TK-184 Morshanskiy Zheleznodorozhnik||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Soviet Union|1935}}\n|desc=The D-3-class motor torpedo boat was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/russia/ru_cf_d3.htm|title=D-3 class motor torpedo boat, USSR |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-235||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] was [[depth charge]]d and sunk in the [[Kattegat]] ({{coord|57|44|N|10|39|E}} by {{ship|German torpedo boat|T17||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of all 47 crew.<ref name=U235>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u235.htm |title=U-235 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=10 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-1206||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|des